<br>
As far as the college thing goes, I could have went to college to become an electronic tech, instead I chose to serve my country which I did for six years.  I took the ASVAB and scored the best in electronics so they pushed me that way.  I became a 68X Armament Electrical repairer on the AH 64 Apache.  That means I fixed the electronic systems and also loaded the aircraft.  <br>
<br>
I don't understand why you are bringing up combat arms in this thing because quite frankly I was deployed three times and while the infantry sat back in camp and got those 7 hours of sleep, I was running missions and doing jump FARPS.  While the infantry sat in the chow hall complaining about how good we had it, I was getting wind blown out on a launch pad by a helicopter.  Also once a war was to kick off, my job would be to ride on a black hawk with ammo behind enemy lines, set up a FARP, and hope to god the enemy didn't find us while we loaded aircraft and refueled them.  Know what, I wasn't considered combat arms.  Please stop with the dividing up how hard each section of things are until you know more about what each section does. <br>
<br>
What this &quot;punk&quot; is doing is standing up for soldiers.  He is tired of seeing crap attitudes come from people who think we get too much and deserve less than what we get.  I mean come on, its the soldier that insures we have the freedom that we do, at least the government could do is raise thier pay to just above welfare status. <br>
