<br>
A married E-5/E-6's BAH is around 25-45 more than a single E-5's/E-6's BAH.  (Depending on where you're stationed).  I'm sorry, but my kids go through a lot more than 25-45 dollars in diapers a month (if yer about to have a kid, screw Huggies/Luvs, go with Dri-Bottoms.  Cheaper, and imo, better quality.)<br>
<br>
Anyhow, sorry to get everyone so wound up.  Admins, feel free to move this to the flame board, if you want.<br>
<br>
Qut's- I started out in combat arms (12B).  I re-classed to my current MOS, Apache Armament/Electrical specialist after 6 years.  Like you, I had the same attitude about &quot;rear-d pogues, etc, etc, etc.&quot;  That just shows how narrow minded I, and YOU really are.  Ask the boys of the 504th and 505th PIR how happy they are to see an Apache fly overhead, providing close air support.  Ask those same folks how happy they are to get they're &quot;3 hots and a cot&quot; delivered to them by other folks riding on a blackhawk or chinook, 'cause driving a convoy is too unsafe to get the job done.  These days, it's a team effort to get anything done.  As for all the training I've received.....  for an aviation MOS, it's a 6 YEAR initial enlistment, to ensure the government gets their monies worth out of you.  By the way... I work hard now in garrison than I ever did.  The almighty OR rate (operational readiness) is king. <br>
<br>
My main point, and the issue I was trying to bring to light was, the 1st term enlisted guy, newly married (i.e, within the past 2 years or so), with/without a kid.  Many of these folks are a single income family (wether because the spouse is struggling to keep a semblance of normal family life together while trying to get through school/ a training program of some sort, or raising a child) that are forced to apply for WIC, food stamps, and any sort of local grant they can get to make ends meet.  Please, take the blinders off, and take a good look at the issue I presented.  I agree, combat arms non-coms are true patriots (and they do receive other compensation; re-enlistment bonuses are typically much higher, and in garrison, workloads are light enough for the motivated ones to complete much work on college degrees), but does that mean the rest of us aren't?<br>
<br>
SSG Wulfy<br>
