<br>
I do agree with you on the NCO issue.  An NCO is part-time counselor, baby-sitter, and more.  The maturity level of the recruits we get these days is nowhere near where it was.  Many are arriving at their first duty station with a pile of debt.  Some of them have no clue how to balance a check book.  Initial Entry Training (the new, &quot;politically correct&quot; name for basic training) has been hamstrung.  While some of the changes are for the better, many of the changes are perceived to be &quot;coddling&quot; the newest member of the service.  We get recruits straight from training now, that have never passed a PT test.  It's no longer a requirement.  That's right, to get out of Basic/AIT, the only requirement is to stay out of trouble.  You only need 50 points per event on the PT test (as opposed to 60), and we've even gotten a few that hadn't qualified on their rifle.  What's that mean?  It means we have to not only handle all the normal duties and details of the day, but also try and educate these kids on a multitude of subjects.  The average soldier we get straight from training is simply not equipped to care for himself and/or his family.  The frugality of previous generations simply isn't there in many of these kids.  Once you get them straightened out, and educate them on personal/family finance, a sense of pride, and mission accomplishment, many of them are great soldiers, and a true asset.  It's those soldiers I'd love to help!  <br>
<br>
Anyhow, how'd that rant get started....  *shrug*<br>
<br>
Oh,... my wife's in too, so we're doin' pretty good on finances at the moment.  But when we first got married (E-4 &amp; E-3), and had our first child, it was a struggle for us.  Even with both paychecks, it was a stretch.  We definately needed advice on finances.  Fortunately, we had a great platoon sergeant, and caring family members that got us straightened out.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://216.40.249.192/mysmilies/contrib/guus/tong.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><center>
