<br>
When I first entered the service, it was NOT for money (I left a well paying job), it was NOT for a &quot;get out of town free card&quot; (I came back when I was done), it was NOT for training (not even close to what I do now).<br>
<br>
I entered the service to serve my country.  I have a family history in the armed services, my dad (16 years), his dad (8 years), his dad (10 years)... and it was my turn.  It was NOT forced on me.  It was my choice to enter (although I was limited on what I was allowed to choose, for fear of a good beating).<br>
<br>
I agree that 90% of todays newly enlisted join the service for reasons OTHER THAN to just serve OUR coutry, but please be mindful of those of us who don't.<br>
<br>
Since my first station in Germany, I had a second job at the enlisted club.  And I kept that job for 3 years and 4 months to help pay the bills of a growing family (read- wife and child).  While you GET money for living off-base (in APPROVED housing), you don't always get enough to pay the rent (read-some comes out of your own pocket).  You also needed to purchase a car, gas and insurance (more from your own pocket), the base exchange did not always have in-stock the supplies you needed (read-diapers or whatever), and hell... god forbid if you smoked (read-paid more for them on-base then off).  <br>
<br>
But yes, I survived (although some may not like it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .. ), I lived to walk, talk, drink, work, love and play with my family and friends.  <br>
<br>
The ONLY larger oxymoron than &quot;military intelligence&quot;... is &quot;adaquate military pay&quot;<br>
<br>
